<DOC><DOCNO> AP890626-0072 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 1133EST</FILEID><FIRST>u i PM-Afghan-Prisoners     06-26 0321</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Afghan-Prisoners,0334</SECOND><HEAD>Rebels Say Soviets Agree To Exchange Prisoners En Masse</HEAD><BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Afghan government will free rebelprisoners in exchange for Soviet soldiers captured by guerrillasduring the 10-year-old war, rebel sources said today.   Soviet diplomats, however, said final approval of the prisonerswap must come from the Soviet-backed government in Kabul.   An exchange agreement was reached at a fourth round of talkstoday between Moslem guerrilla representatives and the SovietEmbassy in Islamabad, a guerrilla spokesman said on condition ofanonymity.   He said both sides will exchange lists of prisoners at talks tobe held within the next week.   He said the Soviets endorsed the principle of exchangingprisoners at one time, en masse, as previously demanded by theinsurgents.   A Soviet Embassy statement, however, said Moscow will open talkswith Kabul on the proposed exchange.   ``If the Russians agreed then Kabul will also,'' the guerrillaspokesman said.   The guerrillas claim 40,000 of their people are missing in action.   They say they are holding between 50 and 75 Soviet soldiersinside Afghanistan. Moscow says 311 of its troops have gone missingsince its sent troops to bolster the Kabul government's fightagainst the anti-communist guerrillas nine years ago. The last RedArmy troops withdrew in February under a U.N.-brokered agreement.   This latest round of prisoner negotiations comes while aneight-member Soviet delegation is visiting Pakistan, including threemothers and a father of Red Army soldiers missing in Afghanistan.They insist their group is unofficial.   Delegation spokesman Iona Andronov said that over the past twodays, ``We spoke with the proper people in Moscow and Kabul'' andreceived assurances that ``we can arrange for this exchange.''   The Soviet parents sought information about their children duringa meeting last week with guerrilla leaders in Pakistan's frontiercity, Peshawar.   Andronov said the delegation promised to reciprocate withinformation about missing Afghan guerrillas.</TEXT></DOC>